metadata.name: Audio Visual Harmonics III #19
metadata.description:
See Sound. Hear Light.

Extending "Audio Visual Harmonics" and "Audio Visual Harmonics II", this piece generates a unique, rhythmic, audio visual patch.  Complex musical progressions are more rare.  
 
Visuals are entirely defined by the audio; what you see is what you hear.

Best viewed on a decent GPU for 60fps realtime rendering.

metadata.name: Audio Visual Harmonics II #23
metadata.description:
TAP TO PLAY.

Extending "Audio Visual Harmonics", this piece generates a unique harmonic sequence of four oscillators.  The frequency intervals are melodic and span different musical modes. More pure interval steps are more rare.      

Visuals are entirely defined by the audio; what you see is what you hear.  

Best viewed on a decent GPU for 60fps realtime rendering.

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #220
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.

metadata.name: Endless Braids #49
metadata.description:
This generative braid artwork is built in plain JavaScript, and is based on code I wrote several years ago, here updated with new aesthetics and features. This work is motivated by a beautiful mathematical structure called a braid group.

Each unique mint of the token chooses randomized parameters with varying probability weights for the number of strings, their spacing, coloring schemes and resulting color palettes, and crossing sizes, angles and frequency.

Colors are randomly generated from an algorithm, including the background color. Most of the pieces (70% probability) will feature colors from two separate hue intervals; a smaller number (20%) use only one color interval, and even more rare are the Black-White-Color palettes (6%), and the Black-and-White palette (4%).

Most of them scroll up, but approximately 7% of them scroll down.

The braid will endlessly scroll without any repetition in its pattern.

Dan Gries
Twitter: @rectangleworld

metadata.name: Dahlia Pinnata 30 #81
metadata.description: 30-degree variations of a Dahlia Pinnata. The flower was 3D scanned, producing a 15 millions vertices point cloud. The point cloud was then simplified to 350k vertices, in order to be used here. This piece can still be a bit resource intensive. You can click/tap (or press 's') to stop the spinning, this should help if your device is struggling - @smallfly - fxhash genesis

metadata.name: Reconnaissance #21
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe they’re recon from another planet’s civilization — one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium “This is Mars,” Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands — and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for what’s next.


Choose a resolution (1-6) by adding "&scale=4" to the URL in live view.

metadata.name: The View #102
PEGS #116
metadata.description: Taking inspiration from work by Karl Gerstner, Armin Hofmann, Nick Kuder and Dmitri Cherniak, PEGS explores the limits of constrained algorithmic variation. Based on the simple, playful idea of wrapping a string across a board of pegs, it shows how endless possibilities can be achieved with just a basic set of rules and a few primary colors. When done right, generative art challenges us to answer fundamental questions around creativity, beauty, and life itself.

metadata.name: Hatch Field 001 #142
metadata.description:
Genesis p5js drawing on fx(hash). Experimenting with translating recent work in done in Grasshopper exploring hatch patterns to p5.js. By Andrew Kudless / Matsys @matsysdesign
There are four feature groups:
- Base Hue: Red, Orange, Yellow, Spring Green, Green, Ocean Green, Cyan, Sky Blue, Blue, Purple, Magenta, and Crimson. Each has the same random chance of being the base color (12%).
- Hue Range: Narrow (14%), Wide (51%), and Infinite(34%)
- Lineweight: Thin (75%), Medium (10%), Thick (10%), Extra Thick (5%)
-Fray: Loose (90%), Tight (10%)
